\section{Conclusion and Discussion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
By resolving the fast-slow geometry of nocturnal boundary layer collapse, we show that the sudden decay of turbulent mixing is governed by a boundary-mediated transition on a low-dimensional manifold. Integrating smooth hyperbolic regularizations and state-dependent safeguard gates resolves the numerical singularities that frequently plague meteorological solvers, while our physical parameterizations correctly distinguish between the high-roughness mechanical resilience of CASES99 and the early, cooling-driven collapse observed over the smooth snowpacks of FLOSS.

This geometric framework provides the analytical foundation necessary to resolve intermittent turbulence and nocturnal cycle transitions directly from the underlying physical equations without relying on artificial, discontinuous switching rules.

